ENGR 222 Thermodynamics Winter 2021-2022 Lab 1
¶

BOYLE'S LAW EXPERIMENT¶

In this lab, you will examine the relationship between pressure and volume for an ideal gas. By now, you should understand the ideal gas equation:

$$ PV = mRT $$
In the 1600s, Robert Boyle and his assistants experimentally measured the relationship between pressure and volume of a fixed amount of gas at constant temperature. They determined that pressure and volume were inversely related, which led to the development of Boyle’s Law:

$ P\propto\frac{1}{V}\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ OR\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ P=\frac{C}{V} $

where $ C $ is some constant. When Boyle’s Law is combined with Charles’s Law and Gay-Lussac’s Law (look them up), we arrive at the ideal gas equation.

In this lab, you will measure pressure, temperature, and volume of air in a closed system with an oil surface acting as a free moving piston. You will compare your results to theoretical results calculated using Boyle’s Law. You may work with a classmate (i.e., teams of 2) for the lab report write up. For the data collection portion, you may pair up with another group (i.e., 2 teams of 2; no more than 4 people).

PROCEDURE¶

  1. Record the internal diameter of the test cylinder located on the right side of the apparatus. This diameter will be used in your volume calculations.
  2. You will be recording the following: gage pressure (the gauge is located in the top right corner of the apparatus), the height of air in the right column (using the digital “dial-caliper”-looking device on the right side of the cylinder), and the temperature (using the temperature sensor located on top of the apparatus).
  3. If it hasn’t been done already, open the air vents on top of both cylinders (turn valves to the upward positions) and make sure the temperature sensor is plugged in. The pressure gauge should be reading $ 0 bar $. This will serve as your first pressure measurement.
  4. Shut both air vents by rotating them $ 90 ^\circ $ clockwise (i.e. they will face right). Record the temperature using the digital sensor.
  5. Using the pointer on the digital height measurement device, move the point to the top of the cylinder and press “Zero” to zero it out (make sure the units are in mm). Then move the pointer down to the top of the oil level in the right cylinder. Record this length (ignore the negative sign) to help you calculate the volume of air in the right tank.
  6. If it hasn’t been connected already, connect the vacuum hand pump to the vacuum connection and make sure the handle is facing the vacuum.
  7. Using the vacuum pump, SLOWLY pull a $ 0.1 bar $ vacuum (i.e. $ -0.1 $ gage pressure). This should cause the oil level to change. Monitor the temperature during this process as adjusting the pressure may cause a temperature change; the slower you adjust the pressure, the smaller the temperature difference (think quasi-equilibrium process). If the temperature change is greater than $ 2 ^\circ C $, wait for the temperature to stabilize.
  8. Move the height pointer to the new oil level (there is no need to re-zero the device) and record the new height along with the gage pressure and temperature.
  9. DO NOT VENT THE TEST CYLINDER AT THIS POINT.
  10. If not already connected, connect the bicycle pump to the other pressure port (next to the vacuum port) and turn the handle to the pressure port.
  11. Using the bicycle pump, SLOWLY increase the pressure in the test cylinder to $ +0.2 bar $; this should cause the oil level to change. Like last time with the vacuum pump, monitor the temperature; if the temperature change is above $ 2 ^\circ C $, wait for it to stabilize. Move the pointer to get the new height and record the pressure, temperature, and height.
  12. Repeat step 11 by increasing the pressure to $ 0.4 bar $ SLOWLY.
  13. Repeat step 11 by increasing the pressure by another $ +0.2 bar $ to $ 0.6 bar $ SLOWLY. At this point you should have 5 sets of (pressure, temperature, and height) data (1 under a vacuum, 1 at atmospheric pressure, and 3 with positive gauge pressure measurements).
  14. SLOWLY open the air vent on the reservoir cylinder and allow it to return to atmospheric pressure.

LAB MEMO FORMAT¶

You may team up with one classmate (i.e. form a team of 2) to write this lab memo. The lab memo must be computer generated and will be submitted using the Turnitin.com link on Moodle. Be sure to have page numbers (except the title page) and check for spelling and grammar. The set up should follow the following format:

Title Page¶

Make sure both team members’ names are on the front page. Also put the name of the lab, the course and course section, and the due date.

Determine the percent difference between the exponent you calculated and the exponent it should be using Boyle’s Law.

Make a second X-Y plot with $ \frac{1}{V} $ as the x-axis and absolute pressure as the y-axis and use a linear trend line with a x-intercept set at $ 0 $ (again, be sure you put the equation on the graph). Using your recorded temperatures, the mass you just calculated, and the gas constant for air, calculate C and compare it (i.e. find the percent difference) to the slope from your graph and compare it to the values obtained from your table.

Discussions and Conclusions Sections¶

Comment on how well your data agrees with Boyle’s Law. Comment on possible sources of error that may have caused any discrepancies between your calculated data and the expected theoretical data using Boyle’s Law.

Sample Calculation¶

Without the use of Excel, show you calculations for one data set; i.e. pick one pressure, temperature, and height from your raw data and show the math you used to complete the table with the polished data (i.e. absolute pressure, absolute temperature, etc.). Also show how you computed the volume, mass of air, (using $ m R T $), the percent differences, and an example of any other calculation you did. You may neatly write these calculations on white printer paper and scan it into your report or you may use Equation Editor in Word or you may use MathCad. Be sure to include your units.
